LSU Baseball is back at The Box tonight as the Tigers take on Southeastern! Steal a Deal with 50% off select food and drinks until first pitch. First pitch is at 6:30 pm, and Gate 0 opens at 5:00 pm. We'll see you there!
The Box student section is right field general admission, please enter through Gate 0. Students are encouraged to sit as close to the field as possible and cheer loudly for the Tigers!

To minimize delays entering the Box, please arrive early, have your tickets downloaded in advance to your mobile wallet, and have the ticket pulled up as you approach the gate.

Please be advised that baseball student tickets CANNOT be shared via screenshot.

Folks,


For submitting the final project, please, make sure you submit all files that are needed to build the project, i.e., including lexical analysis, parsing, semantic analysis, and storage allocation.

Also, Brandon observed that groups that have been relying more on using AI tools seem to have been doing worse.  If you are using AI tools, please, make sure that you check that the generated code makes sense.  You are trading off development time for testing time.  With AI-generated code, you need to invest more time in code review and testing than if you wrote the code yourself.

Cheers,

Gerald

,School

PhD students are invited to participate in the American Society for Engineering Education (ASEE) Doctoral Experience Survey. Initial findings from this important study will be published in Fall 2025.

Applications for NASA L’SPACE Open Soon




The NASA L'SPACE Program is a free, online, interactive experience open to undergraduate and graduate STEM students interested in pursuing a career with NASA or other space organizations. 


L'SPACE consists of two Academies — the Mission Concept Academy, and the NASA Proposal Writing and Evaluation Experience Academy. Students may participate in one Academy per semester. Each 12-week Academy is designed to provide unique, hands-on learning and insight into the dynamic world of the space industry. Students can expect to learn NASA mission procedures and protocols from industry professionals as they collaborate with fellow team members to complete mission-related team-projects.

Requirements for participation: Students must be enrolled in a US college or University as an undergrad (graduate students may apply to NPWEE); have access to a computer with internet, webcam, and headset capabilities; and have time to devote an additional 6-10 hours per week, beyond the online session requirements, towards team projects.

Dear Andrew,

Please access the online course evaluations via the “Course Eval” link located in Student Services on your MyLSU Portal. Additionally, you will see a link to the course evaluation system via the home page of Moodle. 


• Sunday May 4th at 11:59 - course evaluation window will close


When completing the evaluation:

• Select the response that best reflects your experiences with the course.
• To save your answers and move onto the next section, just click "NEXT". 
• Remember to click the “SUBMIT” button after you complete each survey.
• If you are unable to complete the survey in one session, make sure to save your review by clicking the “SAVE” button. 

The responses and feedback you provide will always remain anonymous, and overall results will not be released until after final grades have been posted. Because your feedback is important, we may send reminders after a few days if we haven't received your reply.

We greatly appreciate your participation. 

Sincerely,

“Upholding Devotion to the Standards and Dignity of the Engineering Profession”

 

The College of Engineering is excited to again announce the Order of the Engineer program this Spring. The Order of the Engineer was initiated in the United States to foster a spirit of pride and responsibility in the engineering profession. Candidates are inducted into the Order of the Engineer through a Ring Ceremony where they formally accept the Obligation of an Engineer and receive a stainless-steel ring to be worn as a symbol. The Order is not a membership organization; there are never any meetings to attend or dues to pay. Instead, the Order fosters a unity of purpose and the honoring of one’s pledge lifelong.

 

The Order of the Engineer is for engineers who will receive a degree in the following majors: Biological Engineering, Chemical Engineering, Civil Engineering, Environmental Engineering, Computer Engineering, Electrical Engineering, Mechanical Engineering, Industrial Engineering, and Petroleum Engineering. Graduating engineering graduate students or graduate students with an undergraduate engineering degree are also eligible to participate.

 

Every Fall and Spring semester the CoE hosts a Ring Ceremony for any graduating students who wish to be inducted. The Spring ceremony will be held in person on Thursday, May 8, from 3:00 pm- 4:00 pm in Patrick F. Taylor Hall, Room 1202. The event is open to the public and hosted by the Louisiana Engineering Society and the LSU College of Engineering.

 

Students who are graduating in Sprin 2025 can sign up to participate by clicking on this link <https://nam04.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fform.jotform.com%2F250825855173159&data=05%7C02%7Cangu248%40lsu.edu%7Cc2c417799b8f4a40fe8d08dd867fd891%7C2d4dad3f50ae47d983a09ae2b1f466f8%7C0%7C0%7C638814606000351071%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJFbXB0eU1hcGkiOnRydWUsIlYiOiIwLjAuMDAwMCIsIlAiOiJXaW4zMiIsIkFOIjoiTWFpbCIsIldUIjoyfQ%3D%3D%7C0%7C%7C%7C&sdata=T6A2PHxwXHAazQSiXFUA%2FsOBJDxGYoSqZjIerTh41zk%3D&reserved=0>  and submitting their $13 cash or check (for ring/certificate) to College of Engineering Student Services (2228 Patrick F. Taylor Hall).

 

Checks should be made out to “LSU Foundation.” The deadline to sign up for the Spring ceremony is Friday, May 2nd, by 5pm. You will need to submit your ring size on the application. Please note that rings are to be worn on the pinky finger of your writing/working hand. If you aren’t sure what size to order, you can get measured at the Barnes and Nobles on campus anytime at the Customer Service desk.

Dear Student:

 

Congratulations on your candidacy for graduation! 

 

Please complete the survey now https://bit.ly/Spring25Engr <https://nam04.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fbit.ly%2FSpring25Engr&data=05%7C02%7Cangu248%40lsu.edu%7Cdf2126185e0f4200548108dd866fa31c%7C2d4dad3f50ae47d983a09ae2b1f466f8%7C0%7C0%7C638814536376260704%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJFbXB0eU1hcGkiOnRydWUsIlYiOiIwLjAuMDAwMCIsIlAiOiJXaW4zMiIsIkFOIjoiTWFpbCIsIldUIjoyfQ%3D%3D%7C0%7C%7C%7C&sdata=FdBKECaiYCSbcBjvvBXjVD6lx0qwIc4nVrgsDt81Flc%3D&reserved=0>  to share your current plans for after graduation. If you find a new opportunity later, you can come back to the survey to submit an updated response.

 

Your participation in this brief survey by May 31st allows our office and the LSU Olinde Career Center to measure success in preparing students for their careers or graduate school.

 

If you are currently seeking employment or admission to graduate school, please be sure to complete the survey above, and you can schedule a career coaching  Appointments | Handshake <https://nam04.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Flsu.joinhandshake.com%2Fedu%2Fappointments&data=05%7C02%7Cangu248%40lsu.edu%7Cdf2126185e0f4200548108dd866fa31c%7C2d4dad3f50ae47d983a09ae2b1f466f8%7C0%7C0%7C638814536376273340%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJFbXB0eU1hcGkiOnRydWUsIlYiOiIwLjAuMDAwMCIsIlAiOiJXaW4zMiIsIkFOIjoiTWFpbCIsIldUIjoyfQ%3D%3D%7C0%7C%7C%7C&sdata=jqCR4p2PynN4xMolwJ6r83voqNIbLccWJT1ZIR4em4c%3D&reserved=0>   with the engineering career coach, Brady Adamowicz,  for one-on-one support, including virtual and in-person appointments, to help you reach your post-grad goals. You can also access the LSU Career Center <https://www.lsu.edu/careercenter/index.php/>  resources and have access to Handshake even after graduation.  

 

You will receive a post-graduation follow-up survey that assesses your career and graduate school situation through six months past graduation. Each of these surveys is a very important tool for the University, and we sincerely appreciate your feedback on each.

 

Thank you,

STOP! READ THIS E-MAIL CAREFULLY FROM BEGINNING TO FINISH! 

Dear Students in ART 1001,

This week, you should complete your studies of Module 7 (the last one), covering Avant-Garde Movements of the Twentieth Century to Postmodernism. You should furthermore review Modules 6 to 7, as this material is covered on our Final Exam (Exam 3), opening Monday and closing Wednesday of Finals' Week (two weeks from now), concluding the class. 

We still have two important pieces of business to take care of before the end of the semester. MAKE SURE TO COMPLETE ASSIGNMENTS BY THE DEADLINES:

Complete Quiz 7 any time before May 2 (this Friday) at 7:00 p.m. CST.

AND

Final Exam/Exam #3 (covering Modules 6 to 7): Complete Exam any time between Monday, May 5, 7:00 a.m. and Wednesday, May 7, 7:00 p.m. CST


The Final can be found under the “Exam 3” link on the left toolbar (bottom) on Moodle. You can take the exam online and at a time that is convenient for you during the three-day window when it is open. The format and question type are identical with the quizzes, but there are 25 questions this time. As always, once you start the exam, you must complete it in one session. No re-openings, no re-takes.

There is a sample exam posted under the link with the recorded lectures (“Lecture Recordings & Sample Exams/Quiz Questions”) on Moodle.

Remember, quizzes can be taken at any time; exams only during the designated, three-day window.

As always ...

please note that you can take Quizzes and Exams only once. No re-takes, no "second attempts." Once you open it and take it, it's a done deal. Therefore, make sure to be prepared and be familiar with the materials AND have stable internet/Wi-Fi as well as stable electricity before you start Quizzes and Exams. Once you start a Quiz or an Exam, you must complete it. The technical set up is such that if you leave or interrupt a Quiz or an Exam, you cannot return to complete it later (you will no longer be able to access it).

Please plan accordingly.

Best wishes,

Darius A. Spieth

Angel Reese Returns to the PMAC in 1 Week

Students, your #7 ranked LSU Baseball team returns to the Box this weekend to take on #6 Tennessee in a top-ten matchup! This weekend is Alumni Weekend, and the series begins on Friday at 6:30 p.m.

The first 3,000 fans at Friday's game will receive a free Alex Box Stadium - Skip Bertman Field Stadium Replica courtesy of Our Lady of the Lake Health! The first 100 students will receive a concessions voucher for a free hot dog, popcorn, and 22 oz. drink, courtesy of Coach Johnson!

Then, on Sunday's game, the first 2,000 fans will receive a free hat, courtesy of Louisiana Blue! Fans are encouraged to wear gold on Sunday to support Your Fighting Tigers. Gates open 1.5 hours before first pitch for each game. Be there and be loud!
The Box student section is right field general admission, please enter through Gate 0. Gate 0 opens 90 minutes before first pitch. Students are encouraged to sit as close to the field as possible and cheer loudly for the Tigers!

Dear CSE Students and Faculty,
Get ready for another electrifying edition of the Silicon Bayou Guest Speaker Series!
We’re thrilled to welcome Avni Rambhia, Principal Project Manager at Amazon Web Services Cryptography, to campus for a dynamic talk you won’t want to miss:
🎤 “Quantum Leaps: How Quantum Computing is Transforming Development and Cryptography”
🗓️ Monday, April 28, 2025
🕛 12:00 PM
📍 Room 1202, Patrick F. Taylor Hall
From space tech to secure messaging, quantum computing is changing the rules—and Avni’s bringing insights straight from the cutting edge of AWS. Whether you're a future cryptographer or just quantum-curious, this talk will offer real-world challenges, breakthroughs, and a townhall-style Q&A that puts you in the driver’s seat.
💥 Refreshments will be provided—come hungry for knowledge (and snacks)!
Let’s pack the room and show Avni the power of Tiger pride and CSE spirit.
Hope to see you there!

*	View your Saved Schedule and then click the Register button (this button will only appear once your registration appointment is open)
*	Review the courses and section dates/times selected in your saved schedule, then click Register.
*	You’ll see a confirmation screen showing the courses you’ve successfully registered for. You can also review scheduled courses or make changes in your academics hub. Dear LSU Student,

You have been randomly selected to participate in the National College Health Assessment (NCHA) sponsored and distributed by the American College Health Association (ACHA). The ACHA-NCHA is a survey designed to assess student health behaviors in order to provide better services and support for Louisiana State University (LSU) students. You may benefit by knowing that you have assisted in providing accurate information regarding health/wellness behaviors on our campus. The information will be used to inform wellness programs and services.

The NCHA-Web is completed online via the Internet. We encourage you to complete the survey in one sitting, which typically takes about 20-30 minutes. All students who submit a survey will be automatically entered in a random drawing for one of the following items:

*	Premium 40 oz Stainless Steel Tumblers – Keep your drinks perfectly cold or hot for hours with this high-quality, durable tumbler.
*	Dining Hall Passes – Savor convenient, tasty meals with this exclusive pass for easy access to delicious dining options.
*	Exciting LSU Swag Bags – Show off your LSU pride in style with a curated selection of awesome gear and treats, including free Nothing Bundt Cakes and refreshing Jeremiah's Ice!

There may be some personal discomfort with the content of certain questions. For example, there are questions regarding illegal substance use, interpersonal violence, and sexual behavior. If you’d like to talk with someone about issues addressed in the survey, you may contact the LSU Student Health Center by calling 225-578-5718.

Your participation is completely voluntary and confidential. To ensure confidentiality, e-mail addresses are destroyed by ACHA before data are compiled and shared with LSU. The raw data file that is shared with your school will not contain any unique identifiers. If you feel that answering specific demographic questions might reveal your identity, you may leave them blank. You may answer only some questions, or you may choose not to participate in the survey at all. Any reports or publications based on this research will use only group data and will not identify you or any individual as being affiliated with this project.

By taking this survey, you consent to participate in the study and agree that the purpose of this study has been satisfactorily explained to you. You understand you are free to discontinue participation at any time if you so choose and that the researcher will gladly answer any questions that may arise during the course of the research. Refusing or withdrawing from this study will be at no penalty or loss of benefits to you.

You may contact the principal investigator, Carli DiLorenzo, at the Student Health Center at 225-578-8516 or healthpromotion@lsu.edu if you have questions or concerns about the survey. If you would like to talk with someone about the issues addressed in this survey, you are encouraged to contact the LSU Student Health Center by calling 225-578-5718 or to contact one of these national resources <https://nam04.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.acha.org%2Fncha%2Fresources%2Fresources-for-students%2Fresources-for-students-in-us%2F&data=05%7C02%7Cangu248%40lsu.edu%7C6f5f543179dd4325c7fd08dd8267689a%7C2d4dad3f50ae47d983a09ae2b1f466f8%7C0%7C0%7C638810102837055892%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJFbXB0eU1hcGkiOnRydWUsIlYiOiIwLjAuMDAwMCIsIlAiOiJXaW4zMiIsIkFOIjoiTWFpbCIsIldUIjoyfQ%3D%3D%7C0%7C%7C%7C&sdata=Md1Bfs2XMbEOCJhJltbZWhISYnsEORBcdfd%2BTnsut%2FY%3D&reserved=0> . For 24-hour crisis or emotional support call or text 225-924-5781, ThePhone. ThePhone is a 24– hour crisis counseling and support line serving the students of LSU. Callers to the LSU line are connected to volunteer paraprofessional counselors trained in crisis intervention and suicide prevention.

Data transmission is encrypted and firewall securities are in place. After you submit the survey to the secure server, a message thanking you for taking the NCHA-Web will be displayed in your browser window, and you will receive a confirmation email.

The LSU Institutional Review Board looked at the project and determined it did not need a formal review.
